00:00:00.373 --> 00:00:02.927
- [Voiceover] Let's say we
have the function f of x

00:00:02.927 --> 00:00:07.094
which is equal to cosine
of x to the third power

00:00:08.477 --> 00:00:10.561
which we could also write like this,

00:00:10.561 --> 00:00:13.394
cosine of x to the third power.

00:00:14.846 --> 00:00:16.892
And we are interested in figuring out

00:00:16.892 --> 00:00:21.139
what f prime of x is going to be equal to.

00:00:21.139 --> 00:00:25.751
So we want to figure out f
prime of x and as we will see,

00:00:25.751 --> 00:00:28.574
the chain rule is going
to be very useful here

00:00:28.574 --> 00:00:29.407
and what I'm going to do is

00:00:29.407 --> 00:00:31.235
I'm going to first just
apply the chain rule

00:00:31.235 --> 00:00:32.489
and then maybe dig into it a little bit

00:00:32.489 --> 00:00:34.052
to make sure we draw the connection

00:00:34.052 --> 00:00:36.327
between what we're doing here
and then what you might see

00:00:36.327 --> 00:00:38.163
in maybe some of your Calculus textbooks

00:00:38.163 --> 00:00:39.958
that explain the chain rule.

00:00:39.958 --> 00:00:42.328
So if we have a function

00:00:42.328 --> 00:00:45.264
that is defined as essentially
a composite function,

00:00:45.264 --> 00:00:47.880
notice this expression right here,

00:00:47.880 --> 00:00:50.410
we are taking something
to the third power.

00:00:50.410 --> 00:00:52.534
It isn't just an x that we're
taking to the third power.

00:00:52.534 --> 00:00:55.475
We are taking a cosine
of x to the third power.

00:00:55.475 --> 00:00:57.601
So we're taking a function,
you could view it this way,

00:00:57.601 --> 00:00:59.643
we're taking the function cosine of x

00:00:59.643 --> 00:01:01.847
and then we're inputting
it in to another function

00:01:01.847 --> 00:01:04.788
that takes it to the third power.

00:01:04.788 --> 00:01:06.218
So let me put it this way.

00:01:06.218 --> 00:01:07.940
If you viewed,

00:01:07.940 --> 00:01:10.430
if you say, look, we could take an x,

00:01:10.430 --> 00:01:14.430
we put it into one function and that is,

00:01:14.430 --> 00:01:17.086
that first function is cosine of x

00:01:17.086 --> 00:01:19.753
so first, we evaluate the cosine

00:01:21.008 --> 00:01:24.520
and so that's going to
produce cosine of x,

00:01:24.520 --> 00:01:26.316
cosine of x,

00:01:26.316 --> 00:01:28.804
and then we're going to
input it into a function

00:01:28.804 --> 00:01:31.301
that just takes things to the third power.

00:01:31.301 --> 00:01:34.365
So it just takes things
to the third power.

00:01:34.365 --> 00:01:36.806
And so what are you going to end up with?

00:01:36.806 --> 00:01:38.263
Well, you're going to end up with,

00:01:38.263 --> 00:01:39.572
what are you taking to the third power?

00:01:39.572 --> 00:01:41.741
You're taking cosine of x.

00:01:41.741 --> 00:01:44.840
Cosine of x to the third power.

00:01:44.840 --> 00:01:47.763
This is a composite function.

00:01:47.763 --> 00:01:50.022
You could view this,

00:01:50.022 --> 00:01:52.945
you could view this as the function,

00:01:52.945 --> 00:01:55.476
let's call this blue one, the function v

00:01:55.476 --> 00:01:58.743
and let's call this the function u

00:01:58.743 --> 00:02:01.679
and so if we're taking x and into u,

00:02:01.679 --> 00:02:02.846
this is u of x

00:02:04.251 --> 00:02:07.273
and then if we're taking
u of x into the input

00:02:07.273 --> 00:02:09.600
or as the input into the function v

00:02:09.600 --> 00:02:11.787
then this output right over here,

00:02:11.787 --> 00:02:13.870
this is going to be v of,

00:02:15.562 --> 00:02:16.910
well, what was inputted?

00:02:16.910 --> 00:02:17.910
V of u of x.

00:02:18.872 --> 00:02:19.789
V of u of x

00:02:21.932 --> 00:02:23.528
or another way of writing it,

00:02:23.528 --> 00:02:24.713
I'm going to write it multiple ways.

00:02:24.713 --> 00:02:28.430
That's the same thing as v of cosine of x.

00:02:28.430 --> 00:02:29.847
V of cosine of x.

00:02:31.535 --> 00:02:33.619
And so v, whatever you input into it,

00:02:33.619 --> 00:02:35.336
it just takes it to the third power.

00:02:35.336 --> 00:02:36.358
If you were to write v of x,

00:02:36.358 --> 00:02:38.634
it would be x to the third power.

00:02:38.634 --> 00:02:40.036
So the chain rule tells us

00:02:40.036 --> 00:02:41.997
or the chain rule is what
our brain should say.

00:02:41.997 --> 00:02:44.203
Hey, it becomes applicable

00:02:44.203 --> 00:02:46.203
if we're going to take the
derivative of a function

00:02:46.203 --> 00:02:49.753
that can be expressed as a
composite function like this.

00:02:49.753 --> 00:02:53.795
So just to be clear, we can write f of x.

00:02:53.795 --> 00:02:56.628
f of x is equal to v of u of x.

00:02:57.919 --> 00:03:00.232
I know I'm essentially
saying the same thing

00:03:00.232 --> 00:03:01.148
